=== 12.4 Backprop Through a Linear Layer

The most common operation in a transformer is a *linear layer*: stem:[y = Wx].

Given the upstream gradient stem:[\delta = \frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial y}] (arriving from the layer above), the chain rule gives:

[stem]
++++
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial W} = \delta \cdot x^\top
\qquad
\frac{\partial \mathcal{L}}{\partial x} = W^\top \cdot \delta
++++

The first equation tells us how to update stem:[W].
The second passes the gradient backward to whatever fed stem:[x] into this layer.

